Below is an explanation of the teams DataFrame attribtues:

  • Note: Data used was regular season data between 1970-2015. All variables are season statistics. The models are designed to be able to enter the regular season data and predict the team rankings for that season.

Overall: Team rank at end of season
Off_Rank: Team Offensive rank
Team: Team name
Games: Number of games played
Points: Total points scored
Yards: Total yards accumulated
Off_Plays: Total offensive plays executed
Fum_Lost: Total offensive fumbles lost
Fdowns: Total first downs
Pass_Comp: Total completed passes
Pass_Att: Total attempted passes
Pass_Yds: Total passing yards
Pass_TD: Total passing touchdowns
Pass_Int: Total interceptions thrown
Pass_NYPA: Net yards per passing attempt
Pass_1stD: Total passing firstdowns
Rush_Att: Total rushing attempts
Rush_Yds: Total rushing yards
Rush_TD: Total rushing touchdowns
Rush_YPA: Average rushing yards per attemps
Rush_1stD: Total rushing firstdowns
Off_Pen: Total offensive penalties
Off_Pen_Yds: Total offensive penalty yards
Def_Rank: Team Defensive rank
Opp_Points: Total opponent points allowed
Yds_Allowed: Total opponent yards allowed
Def_YPP: Opponent average yards per play
Takeaways: Total takeaways
Fdowns_Allowed: Opponent firstdowns allowed
Pass_Yds_Allowed: Opponent passing yards allowed
Pass_TD_Allowed: Opponent passing touchdowns allowed
Interceptions: Total interceptions
Def_Pass_NYPA: Opponent net yards per passing attempt allowed
Pass_1stD_Allowed: Opponent passing firstdowns allowed
Rush_Yds_Allowed: Opponent rushing yards allowed
Rush_TD_Allowed: Opponent rushing touchdowns allowed
Def_Rush_YPA: Opponent average rushing yards per attempt allowed
Rush_1stD_Allowed: Opponent rushing firstdowns allowed
Def_Pen: Total defensive penalties
Def_Pen_Yds: Total defensive penalty yards

# load the 2016 regular season data
rank = pd.read_csv("data/2016.csv")
rank = pd.DataFrame(rank)

# Use model1 to predict y value; we are still using all available X-variables for this test
columns = rank[['Off_Rank', 'Points', 'Yards', 'Off_Plays', 'Fum_Lost', 'Fdowns', 'Pass_Comp', 'Pass_Att', 
                'Pass_Yds', 'Pass_TD', 'Pass_Int', 'Pass_NYPA', 'Pass_1stD', 'Rush_Att', 'Rush_Yds', 'Rush_TD', 
                'Rush_YPA', 'Rush_1stD', 'Off_Pen', 'Off_Pen_Yds', 'Def_Rank', 'Opp_Points', 'Yds_Allowed', 
                'Def_YPP', 'Takeaways', 'Fdowns_Allowed', 'Pass_Yds_Allowed', 'Pass_TD_Allowed', 'Interceptions', 
                'Def_Pass_NYPA', 'Pass_1stD_Allowed', 'Rush_Yds_Allowed', 'Rush_TD_Allowed', 'Def_Rush_YPA', 
                'Rush_1stD_Allowed', 'Def_Pen', 'Def_Pen_Yds']]
predict = pd.DataFrame(model1.predict(columns))
predict = predict.rename(columns={0: 'Predicted Overall'})

# put the Team and Predicted Overall ranking in a table together and ensure the columns are labeled correctly
predict = pd.DataFrame(zip(rank['Team'], predict['Predicted Overall']))
predict = predict.rename(columns={0: 'Team', 1: 'Predicted Overall'})

predict = pd.merge(predict, actual, on='Team')

# create a new column that contains the percentage change from week 1 to week 2
predict['Difference']= (predict['Predicted Rank'] - predict['Actual Finish'])
predict['% Difference']= (((predict['Predicted Rank'] - predict['Actual Finish']) / predict['Predicted Rank']) * 100)

# clean up the % Change column so it is more appealing, eliminating the decimals
predict['% Difference'] = predict['% Difference'].astype(int)
predict['% Difference'] = predict['% Difference'].abs()

# calculate MSE
mse = 0
count = 0
for i in predict['Difference']:
    count += 1
    mse += (i*i)
model1_mse = float(mse) / float(count)

count = 0
for i in predict['Difference']:
    if i == 0:
        count+=1

a = 0
for i in predict['Difference']:
    a+=1
    if a == 1:
        if i == 0:
            print("THE MODEL CORRECTLY PREDICTED THE SUPERBOWL WINNER!!!")

print '%s %s' %("Number of rankings correctly predicted: ", count)

In [159]:
predict2 = pd.merge(predict2, actual, on='Team')

# create a new column that contains the difference between the predicted rank and the actual rank
predict2['Difference']= (predict2['Predicted Rank'] - predict2['Actual Finish'])
predict2['% Difference']= (((predict2['Predicted Rank'] - predict2['Actual Finish']) / predict2['Predicted Rank']) * 100)

# clean up the % Change column so it is more appealing, eliminating the decimals
predict2['% Difference'] = predict2['% Difference'].astype(int)
predict2['% Difference'] = predict2['% Difference'].abs()

# calculate MSE
mse2 = 0
count = 0
for i in predict2['Difference']:
    count += 1
    mse2 += (i*i)
model2_mse = float(mse2) / float(count)

# count will give us the total number of zeros in the difference column; these are correct predictions
count = 0
for i in predict2['Difference']:
    if i == 0:
        count+=1

# first row of the difference column. If this value is a zero, the model correctly predicted the Super Bowl winner
a = 0
for i in predict2['Difference']:
    a+=1
    if a == 1:
        if i == 0:
            print("THE MODEL CORRECTLY PREDICTED THE SUPERBOWL WINNER!!!")

print '%s %s' %("Number of rankings correctly predicted: ", count)
print '%s %s' %("Model2 Mean Square Error: ", "%.3f" % model2_mse)
predict2

predict3 = pd.merge(predict3, actual, on='Team')

# create a new column that contains the percentage change from week 1 to week 2
predict3['Difference']= (predict3['Predicted Rank'] - predict3['Actual Finish'])
predict3['% Difference']= (((predict3['Predicted Rank'] - predict3['Actual Finish']) / predict3['Predicted Rank']) * 100)

# clean up the % Change column so it is more appealing, eliminating the decimals
predict3['% Difference'] = predict3['% Difference'].astype(int)
predict3['% Difference'] = predict3['% Difference'].abs()

# calculate MSE
mse3 = 0
count = 0
for i in predict3['Difference']:
    count += 1
    mse3 += (i*i)
model3_mse = float(mse3) / float(count)
